commit 7192ebc0cefedcbf44577d18729ddf277888bb56
Author: Daniel Falbel <dfalbel@gmail.com>
Date:   Thu Apr 16 15:59:56 2026 -0300

    Add move semantics and reduce shared_ptr copy overhead (#1444)

    * Return get_shared() by const reference to avoid unnecessary atomic refcount ops

    get_shared() previously returned std::shared_ptr<void> by value, causing
    an atomic reference count increment on every call. Since every copy
    constructor passes the result into XPtrTorch(std::shared_ptr<void> x),
    this meant two atomic increments per copy (one in get_shared(), one in
    the parameter copy). Returning const& eliminates one of them.

    * Add move constructors and return get_shared() by const reference

    - Return get_shared() by const& to avoid an unnecessary atomic refcount
      increment on every call (was returning shared_ptr by value)
    - Add default move constructors to all 39 subclasses that declare explicit
      copy constructors. Without these, C++ suppresses the implicit move
      constructor, forcing copies (with atomic refcount ops) when temporaries
      are passed around.
    - Add corresponding default copy/move assignment operators, since declaring
      a move constructor suppresses the implicit copy assignment operator.

    * Use std::move in make_xptr to avoid redundant shared_ptr copy

    make_xptr takes its argument by value, then copies it again onto the
    heap with `new type(x)`. Since the parameter is about to go out of
    scope, we can move from it instead, avoiding one atomic refcount
    increment/decrement pair per call.
