commit 716ab32aa5810fe7cd7c15ec1b46e7e9a17d8266
Author: Daniel Falbel <dfalbel@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon Apr 6 17:24:15 2026 -0300

    Libtorch2.8 (#1419)

    * Bump to libtorch 2.8.0

    - Update torch_version to 2.8.0
    - Fix Linux libtorch URL format (no longer has cxx11-abi in filename)
    - Add Declarations-2.8.0.yaml generated from PyTorch v2.8.0
    - Update torchgen default version to 2.8.0

    New functions in 2.8.0:
    - _fused_rms_norm
    - _weight_int4pack_mm_with_scales_and_zeros
    - _grouped_mm

    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 <noreply@anthropic.com>

    * Update lantern to build against libtorch 2.8.0

    - Bump TORCH_VERSION to 2.8.0
    - Update Linux URL format (no cxx11-abi in 2.8.0 filenames)

    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 <noreply@anthropic.com>

    * Regenerate lantern headers and R/C++ bindings for libtorch 2.8.0

      - Run lanterngen to update autogen sections in lantern.cpp and lantern.h
      - Run torchgen::generate() to update gen-namespace.R and gen-namespace.cpp
      - Fix bool#no YAML handler to preserve uppercase N parameter names

      The bool#no handler (added in the original 2020 torchgen commit) preserved
      lowercase 'n' but missed uppercase 'N', a latent bug affecting 11 internal
      functions (cudnn_affine_grid_generator, native_group_norm, etc). With
      purrr >= 1.0 this became a hard error during code generation

    * Fix runtime dispatch, GC race, weak linkage, and doc updates for 2.8.0

    - src/codegen.cpp: Move int64_t/double checks above Tensor catch-all so
      plain R numeric scalars dispatch correctly when both types are valid
    - R/ignite.R: Keep tensor R objects alive in extract_ignite_state_dict to
      prevent pyobj_slot GC race with xptr_address matching
    - inst/include/torch.h: Add __attribute__((weak)) for _lantern_* function
      pointers so dyn.load(now=TRUE) on Linux succeeds
    - R/operators.R: Rename %*% formals from e1/e2 to x/y
    - R/gen-namespace-docs.R, man/: Add out_dtype param to addmm/baddbmm/bmm/mm,
      fix Rd escaping in scaled_dot_product_attention

    * Add float8_e4m3fn and float8_e5m2 dtype support

    Expose PyTorch's FP8 scalar types through the full lantern → Rcpp → R
    stack. Available in libtorch 2.8.0+, these dtypes are needed for loading
    FP8-quantized model weights (e.g. safetensors with F8_E4M3 tensors).

    New exports: torch_float8_e4m3fn(), torch_float8_e5m2()

    * Add Rd documentation for float8_e4m3fn and float8_e5m2 dtypes

    Fixes R CMD check WARNING for undocumented code objects.

    * update cmake lists

    * Update CI test matrix to CUDA 12.8

    * Use GitHub-hosted runners for CUDA lantern builds (#1420)

    * Use GitHub-hosted runners for CUDA lantern builds

    * cleanups for containers

    * Revert "cleanups for containers"

    This reverts commit 569c605fc58b82501314928d58de848010706d6b.

    * Add cirun config for CUDA tests on DigitalOcean GPU droplets

    * Revert "Add cirun config for CUDA tests on DigitalOcean GPU droplets"

    This reverts commit 9905efd0ba8a2ea3833793da0fd927963a9c6524.

    * Point CUDA CI to custom libtorch build compatible with CI GPU capability

    * Fix missing runner and r_version in CUDA 12.8 matrix include entry

    * Remove cu12.6 from check matrix and always show dlopen errors

    * Set LD_LIBRARY_PATH for CUDA libs in CI to fix dlopen failures

    The custom libtorch build doesn't bundle CUDA runtime libraries
    (unlike official PyTorch builds), so dlopen needs to find them
    on the system via LD_LIBRARY_PATH.

    * Add library path to verification subprocess

    When torch is installed to a temp directory (e.g. during R CMD check
    or package installation), the verification subprocess can't find the
    torch package because the temp dir isn't on .libPaths(). Pass the
    parent directory of the install path so loadNamespace("torch") works.

    * Use Ubuntu 22.04 CUDA container to match libtorch glibc requirements

    The custom libtorch build was compiled on Ubuntu 22.04 (glibc 2.35),
    so libc10.so requires GLIBC_2.32+. The Ubuntu 20.04 container only
    has glibc 2.31, causing dlopen to fail.

